On Target With PyMC3

Let's look and how we can use PyMC3 to help us improve our aim.

Jul 2, 2020 • 2 min read

Bayesian   PyMC3

  • The situation
  • Lessons learned

The situation

Last weekend I was relaxing in the countryside at a colleague's château, and we decided to take turns shooting at a target with an air rifle. Unfortunately, we were all terrible shots, and the rifle was uncalibrated, which got me thinking about how we could calibrate the rifle in an intellectually principled way.

Let's step back, and make some assumptions.

Firstly, while we are aiming at the center of the target, because the rifle is uncalibrated, the pellets are landing at another location.

Secondly, because of a number of factors, including wind, temperature, humidity, and above all, our terrible aim, the pellets aren't landing where we intend them to.

Let's start modelling the situation in Python.

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pymc3 as pm
from PIL import Image
from warnings import filterwarnings
filterwarnings('ignore')

plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [20,20]
np.random.seed(1337)

Ok, now let's pretend that our rifle is incorrectly calibrated such that, when we are aiming at exactly at the center of the target, our pellets will land 120 units to the right, and 80 pixels down.

Let's also pretend that they will be normally distributed around this point, with a standard deviation of 85 pixels in each axis due to the wind/humidity/our terrible aim.

Let's go ahead and randomly generate the results of 5 shots at the target.

x_observed = np.random.normal(120,85,5)
y_observed = np.random.normal(-80,85,5)

img = Image.open('data/2020-07-02-On-Target-With-PyMC3/1000px-10_m_Air_Rifle_target.svg.png')

plt.imshow(img)
plt.scatter(x_observed+500,500-y_observed,alpha=0.9,s = 1000)

plt.grid()
plt.show()

Ok, now back to reality. Let's say that we have fired off 5 shots, and we have the target above as a result. What adjustments should we make in order to improve our aim?

import pymc3 as pm
with pm.Model() as model: 
    x_offset = pm.Normal('x_offset',mu = 0, sigma=100)
    y_offset = pm.Normal('y_offset',mu = 0, sigma=100)
    standard_deviation = pm.HalfNormal('standard_deviation',sigma=100)    
    
    impact_x = pm.Normal('impact_x', mu = x_offset, sigma = standard_deviation, observed = x_observed)
    impact_y = pm.Normal('impact_y', mu = y_offset, sigma = standard_deviation, observed = y_observed)
    
    trace = pm.sample(draws=10_000, tune=1_000)
